      ],
      "source": "https://buchananny.gov/community/history.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Long before settlers, the Kitchawonke Indians originally inhabited the land that is now Buchanan.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://buchananny.gov/community/history.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "In 1848 a railroad station opened at the end of what is now White Street, sparking local growth.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://buchananny.gov/community/history.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "A tannery opened in 1860 by Strang and White, marking Buchanan’s early industrial era.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://buchananny.gov/community/history.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "The hamlet was once called East Haverstraw, later Centerville, before becoming Buchanan in 1890 for postmaster George Buchanan.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.hvgatewaychamber.com/our-communities/"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Buchanan sits on the eastern bank of the historic Hudson River, about 20 miles from White Plains.",
